453  /-- variation on `assert` where a (possibly incomplete)
454      proof of the assertion is provided as a parameter.
455  
456      ``(h,gs) ← local_proof `h p tac`` creates a local `h : p` and
457      use `tac` to (partially) construct a proof for it. `gs` is the
458      list of remaining goals in the proof of `h`.
459  
460      The benefits over assert are:
461      - unlike with ``h ← assert `h p, tac`` , `h` cannot be used by `tac`;
462      - when `tac` does not complete the proof of `h`, returning the list
463        of goals allows one to write a tactic using `h` and with the confidence
464        that a proof will not boil over to goals left over from the proof of `h`,
465        unlike what would be the case when using `tactic.swap`.
466  -/

1304  /-- See `format!` in `init/meta/interactive_base.lean`.
1305  
1306  The main differences are that `pp` is called instead of `to_fmt` and that we can use
1307  arguments of type `tactic α` in the quotations.
1308  
1309  Now, consider the following:
1310  ```
1311  e ← to_expr ``(3 + 7),
1312  trace format!"{e}"  -- outputs `has_add.add.{0} nat nat.has_add (bit1.{0} nat nat.has_one nat.has_add (has_one.one.{0} nat nat.has_one)) ...`
1313  trace pformat!"{e}" -- outputs `3 + 7`
1314  ```
1315  
1316  The difference is significant. And now, the following is expressible:
1317  
1318  ```
1319  e ← to_expr ``(3 + 7),
1320  trace pformat!"{e} : {infer_type e}" -- outputs `3 + 7 : ℕ`
1321  ```
1322  
1323  See also: `trace!` and `fail!`
1324  -/

1379  For example,
1380  ```
